label day5:
    call day5_morning

    return

label day5_morning:
    
    "They rise from their coffins."

    "Remilia flies over to Flandre."

    r "Wings look the same."

    f "That's good."

    "Flandre flies to the fridge and grabs a rabbit."

    r "Hungry already?"

    f "Not everyone has a tiny appetite."

    r "Guess not. I'll go on ahead."

    f "Ok."

    "Remilia flies to the library."

    p "Hi. No Flandre?"

    r "She stayed behind to eat rabbits."

    p "Ok."

    "A few moments pass, with Remilia standing at the front and Patchouli sitting in her chair."

    r "Hey... how come you made your library all the way out in a forest like this?"

    p "It is well-secluded."

    r "I agree. This library is quite peaceful. Do you like seclusion?"

    p "Yes. No distractions."

    r "Hmm. Do you prefer being alone?"

    p "It depends."

    r "On what?"

    p "How bothersome they are."

    r "Yeah, like a servant that knocks on your door too much."

    p "Something like that."

    r "Have we been bothering you at all?"

    p "No."

    r "Why not?"

    p "You aren't bothersome."

    r "Huh. It feels like this conversation just went in a circle. But that's good to know."

    p "I suppose I was repetitive. But to be blunt, you two have made things interesting, so I have no complaints."

    r "I guess we did."

    "Remilia sits at the table."

    r "I am very curious though. You said you wanted to study vampires, but you've only focused on Flandre's wings. You haven't gone outside of that."

    p "I tried, but you didn't want me to."

    r "What do you mean?"

    p "I supposedly broke vampire etiquette and made you run."

    r "Oh. That."

    p "You looked rather silly in that moment."

    r "If I weren't such a gracious vampire, your life would have ended after such an offense."

    p "But in all seriousness, the wings became a problem I wanted to solve. And so I will."

    r "I am grateful for that."

    p "I imagine seeing your sister fly again will be a delightful moment for you."

    r "Yes. It will. I've been dreaming of it."

    "She looks down."

    r "This was all because of my negligence. I would do anything for it to be fixed. Nothing is more important."

    p "Hm."

    r "So yeah, thanks."

    p "I am merely doing what I want, but I will accept your thanks."

    "They sit in silence for a few moments."

    p "Say, what is it like, having a sister?"

    r "A liability."

    p "Huh?"

    r "But in a good way, I mean. My sister is something to keep safe at all times. If servants are incapable of doing it, I have to."

    p "Oh. I see."

    r "I've never seen your face that confused before. Who's looking rather silly now?"

    p "You should use your words better."

    r "Whatever."

    r "So, having a sister is like a companion. That's a simpler way of putting it. I'm not alone."

    p "Hmm, that's family in general, right?"

    r "Yes. Did your family not want to come?"

    p "I came here silently."

    r "Oh. I see."

    p "I was not needed where I was created."

    r "Um... what does that mean?"

    p "I suppose I will tell you what a Magician is now."

    r "Is it not just magic-user?"

    p "No, it is more than that. It is a separate species from human. One who's body can survive on magical energy alone. Biological needs are removed."

    r "Oh? How does that happen?"

    p "Converting one's body into that state requires a sophisticated form of magic, one that many magic-users never figure out."

    r "Ah, but a smart girl like you figured it out, then?"

    p "No. I am an exception. I was born as a magician."

    r "Ok. How?"

    p "I am not certain. I only know that some form of special magic was used. I would like to figure that out someday."

    r "That's very interesting indeed. It sounds very special."

    p "It is, I suppose. But every shortcut pays a price. My physical vigor is rather... poor."

    r "Hmm, I guess I never see you move much. You float a lot."

    p "Yes. That is why."

    r "If you want to understand the magic, why did you leave? Is it easier to figure out alone?"

    p "That knowledge was never given to me. So I left to pursue my own knowledge."

    r "So, is solving your birth a mission of sorts?"

    p "Not particularly. I like seeking knowledge, and this library allows me to do so without others meddling."

    r "You sure are interested in knowledge, eh?"

    p "Yes, and it has become a most suitable surname."

    r "Surname?"

    p "Yes. I am Patchouli Knowledge."

    r "Go figure. Who named you that?"

    p "I did."

    r "Of course you did."

    "Patchouli smiles to herself. Remilia crosses her arms and puts up her feet."

    r "You really told me a lot about yourself there."

    p "Yes. I did. How curious."

    r "You know, libraries are quite nice. Truly a staple for any good mansion. Though this place is severely lacking in couches."

    p "I haven't seen you touch a book."

    r "That's not the point. It's the atmosphere. Status. A wealth of books conveys a wealth of knowledge."

    p "Does that matter if you don't read them and accumulate said knowledge?"

    r "Nah. That's the librarian's job. Delegation is the most important skill of a noble. Remember that."

    p "How shameless."

    f "Lazy."

    r "Oh, hi Flandre."

    "Patchouli casts her numbness spell."

    f "Nice aim. You can do it from there?"

    p "Yes."

    f "I got bored of reading, so I decided to interrupt your conversation. Sorry."

    r "How long have you been here?"

    f "I got here right after you."

    r "Oh. Ok."

    "Flandre takes a seat."

    f "You two are good friends. I'm jealous now. Don't steal my sister."

    p "That isn't the plan."

    r "She won't magically become my sister. Well, unless there's a spell for that."

    p "There is. But I don't know that one."

    r "See? Nothing to worry about."

    f "Hmph. I didn't mean it like that."

    p "Tomorrow, I have more things to try on your wings. I'm rather confident I'll see a breakthrough. Our sunlight chat was helpful."

    f "Ok!"

    r "Sunlight?"

    f "She wants to test sunlight on your arm. Do you think it will regenerate?"

    r "I am not doing that."

    p "I won't force you if you don't want to."

    f "That would be funny though."

    r "Enough of that. Put your feet on the table like a proper noble."

    f "Heh. That's stupid."

    "She puts them up."

    "They continue to relax at the table for the next few hours, with Patchouli passively researching despite the vampires' distractions."

    "Flandre lets out a big yawn."

    r "I think it's bedtime."

    p "Ok. See you tomorrow."

    r "Is the third bedroom down there yours?"

    p "Yes."

    r "I've never seen you use it."

    p "It is a rather strenuous journey. I rest in here."

    r "Oh, right. And also, you can remove one of the three, we sleep in the same room."

    p "I'm not going down there."

    r "Ah, of course. See you tomorrow then."

    "They leave to the bedroom."

    f "I'm happy you made a friend."

    r "Did you doubt I would?"

    f "Um... kind of."

    "Remilia sighs."

    r "How rude. Of course I did."

    f "Congrats."

    "They retire to their coffins."
    
    return